<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837887600005&r=1&w=2">3rd root server</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837693400003&r=1&w=2">Rem () IMSSS</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198507">1985-07-01 14:30:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426502&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837667426502&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

I agree with JSOL. I suggest people include various debug modes in their
server code such as pretending various root servers are down when they
are really up. One way is for the outgoing packet software to lose any
packet destined for some particular host(s). (The alternative of having
the incoming packet software losing packets from some host will cause the
outgoing packets to be actually resent which might trigger some alarm
at the destination host.) Then we can have three up&amp;running root servers
yet at the same time code can be tested for the case when all three are down.
-------

